Two Embu residents have died of suspected cholera. Twenty-six residents are fighting for their lives in different hospitals across the county. The were admitted with vomiting and diarrhoea. They were receiving treatment in hospitals in Siakago and Runyenjes.  Health executive Jamlek Muturi said the 26 patients admitted in different hospitals have been isolated to prevent spreading of the disease. He said they believe the cholera outbreak has been triggered by consumption of contaminated water. Muturi said they have selected a group of experts who are carrying out tests for water from rivers in the county. He said the county government has banned food hawking and feasting in ceremonies as health officials try to curb the disease.